{"title_page": "Lewis Elton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Lewis Elton\n|birth_name=Ludwig Richard Benjamin Ehrenberg\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1923|3|25}}\n|birth_place=[[T\u00fcbingen]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|2018|9|29|1923|3|25}}\n|death_place= [[Surrey]], England\n|occupation=Physicist, researcher\n|parents={{unbulleted list|[[Victor Ehrenberg (historian)|Victor Ehrenberg]]|Eva Dorothea Sommer}}\n|alma_mater={{unbulleted list|[[Christ's College, Cambridge]]|[[University of Westminster|Regent Street Polytechnic]]|[[University College London]]}}\n|children=[[Ben Elton]]\n|relatives=[[Geoffrey Elton]] <small>(brother)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Lewis Richard Benjamin Elton''' (born '''Ludwig Richard Benjamin Ehrenberg'''; 25 March 1923 \u2013 29 September 2018) was a Jewish, German-born British physicist and researcher into education, specialising in higher education.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[T\u00fcbingen]] to the scholars [[Victor Ehrenberg (historian)|Victor Ehrenberg]] and Eva Dorothea Sommer, Ehrenberg moved with his family to [[Prague]] in 1929, and from there to England in February 1939, to escape [[History of the Jews in Germany#Jews under the Nazis (1933\u201345)|Nazi persecution of the Jews]]. Ehrenberg naturalised as a British subject and changed his name by deed poll in June 1947.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38000 |date=27 June 1947 |page=29972}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38019 |date=18 July 1947 |page=3342}}</ref> He was educated at [[Rydal Penrhos|Rydal School]] in [[Colwyn Bay]], and thereafter at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], the [[University of Westminster|Regent Street Polytechnic]], London, and [[University College London]]. It was from the latter institution that he was awarded his PhD, in 1950.\n\nHe was Professor of Physics at Battersea College of Technology from 1964 until 1970. The College completed its transformation into the [[University of Surrey]] (and its relocation from [[Battersea]] to [[Guildford]]) in 1970.He founded the Institute of Educational Technology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surrey.ac.uk/news/ben-elton-remembers-his-father|title=Ben Elton remembers his father {{!}} University of Surrey|website=www.surrey.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  in 1967, the first of its kind. He was somewhat of a pioneer and innovator in the professional development of university teachers and became Professor of Higher Education in 1970, a post he held until 1988. The Institute became international renowned and his philosophy is one that has been adopted by many universities around the world.\n\nIn 1994 he was appointed Professor of Higher Education at [[University College London]], where he founded the Higher Education Research and Development Unit (now the Centre for the Advancement of Learning and Teaching). He became an honorary professor there in 2003. He was appointed Visiting Professor of Higher Education at [[Manchester University]] in August 2005.\n\nHe was a Fellow of the [[American Institute of Physics]] and a Fellow of the [[Society for Research into Higher Education]]. He was awarded a Lifetime Achievement award at the 2005 Times Higher Awards,<ref>{{Citation | last = Thomson | first = Alan | title = Proud winners and PM sparkle at first awards | newspaper = Times Higher Education | location = London | date   = 2 December 2005 | url    = http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/proud-winners-and-pm-sparkle-at-first-awards/200100.article |accessdate=29 June 2013 }}</ref> at which [[Helena Kennedy|Baroness Kennedy]] said \"there is a polymath quality to this man that points to someone interested in educating the whole person\"<ref>{{Citation |date = December 2005 |title = Manchester wins 'higher education institution of the year' award | journal = UniLife |publisher = The University of Manchester | location = Manchester | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages  = 3 | url=http://documents.manchester.ac.uk/display.aspx?DocID=7361 | accessdate=29 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHis brother was the historian [[Geoffrey Elton]] and he was the father of [[Ben Elton]], a comedian and author. He died in September 2018 at the age of 95.<ref>[https://www.surrey.ac.uk/news/professor-lewis-elton-remembered Professor Lewis Elton remembered]</ref>\n\n==Lewis Elton Gallery, University of Surrey==\nIn 1963 at the Surrey University Battersea campus, Elton started a project to show original artworks in the Physics Department.<ref>http://www.surrey.ac.uk/arts/visualarts/exhibitions%20and%20events/the_elton_art_collection_exhibition.htm</ref> When the University Gallery at Guildford was relocated in 1997, the gallery was dedicated to Elton and was named the [[Lewis Elton Gallery]]. The gallery hosts regular exhibitions of paintings, photographs and sculpture.\n\n==Lewis and Mary Elton Art Collection==\nThe donation of a collection of paintings and [[objets d'art]] was made to [[University of Surrey]] including works by [[Picasso]], [[Chagall]], [[Klee]] and [[Cocteau]]. The gift was marked by an exhibition at [[The Lightbox]] gallery, Woking, in January 2012.<ref>http://www.surrey.ac.uk/arts/visualarts/exhibitions%20and%20events/the_elton_art_collection_exhibition.htm</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[Ehrenberg (surname)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/calt/homepages/LewisElton.htm Biography at University College London]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060904192002/http://www.ied.edu.hk/loap/Prof_Lewis%20Elton.htm Biography at the Hong Kong Institute of Education]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051227115941/http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Units/cgjs/archive/elton_intro.shtml His family papers at Sussex University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120204164605/http://portal.surrey.ac.uk/portal/page?_pageid=887,373545&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL The Lewis Elton Gallery \u2013 old Surrey Uni website]\n*[http://www.surrey.ac.uk/arts/visualarts/lewiseltongallery/index.htm current Lewis Elton Gallery University of Surrey website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elton, Ludwig}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Surrey]]\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:English educational theorists]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English physicists]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:Jews who immigrated to the United Kingdom to escape Nazism]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rydal Penrhos]]\n[[Category:People from Prague]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00fcbingen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Lewis Elton\n|birth_name=Ludwig Richard Benjamin Ehrenberg\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1923|3|25}}\n|birth_place=[[T\u00fcbingen]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|2018|9|29|1923|3|25}}\n|death_place= [[Surrey]], England\n|occupation=Physicist, researcher\n|parents={{unbulleted list|[[Victor Ehrenberg (historian)|Victor Ehrenberg]]|Eva Dorothea Sommer}}\n|alma_mater={{unbulleted list|[[Christ's College, Cambridge]]|[[University of Westminster|Regent Street Polytechnic]]|[[University College London]]}}\n|children=[[Ben Elton]]\n|relatives=[[Geoffrey Elton]] <small>(brother)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Lewis Richard Benjamin Elton''' (born '''Ludwig Richard Benjamin Ehrenberg'''; 25 March 1923 \u2013 29 September 2018) was a Jewish, German-born British physicist and researcher into education, specialising in higher education.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[T\u00fcbingen]] to the scholars [[Victor Ehrenberg (historian)|Victor Ehrenberg]] and Eva Dorothea Sommer, Ehrenberg moved with his family to [[Prague]] in 1929, and from there to England in February 1939, to escape [[History of the Jews in Germany#Jews under the Nazis (1933\u201345)|Nazi persecution of the Jews]]. Ehrenberg naturalised as a British subject and changed his name by deed poll in June 1947.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38000 |date=27 June 1947 |page=29972}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38019 |date=18 July 1947 |page=3342}}</ref> He was educated at [[Rydal Penrhos|Rydal School]] in [[Colwyn Bay]], and thereafter at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], the [[University of Westminster|Regent Street Polytechnic]], London, and [[University College London]]. It was from the latter institution that he was awarded his PhD, in 1950.\n\nHe was Professor of Physics at Battersea College of Technology from 1964 until 1970. As the College completed its transformation into the [[University of Surrey]] (and its relocation from [[Battersea]] to [[Guildford]]) in 1970 he became Professor of Higher Education, a post he held until 1988. In 1994 he was appointed Professor of Higher Education at [[University College London]], where he founded the Higher Education Research and Development Unit (now the Centre for the Advancement of Learning and Teaching). He became an honorary professor there in 2003. He was appointed Visiting Professor of Higher Education at [[Manchester University]] in August 2005.\n\nHe was a Fellow of the [[American Institute of Physics]] and a Fellow of the [[Society for Research into Higher Education]]. He was awarded a Lifetime Achievement award at the 2005 Times Higher Awards,<ref>{{Citation | last = Thomson | first = Alan | title = Proud winners and PM sparkle at first awards | newspaper = Times Higher Education | location = London | date   = 2 December 2005 | url    = http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/proud-winners-and-pm-sparkle-at-first-awards/200100.article |accessdate=29 June 2013 }}</ref> at which [[Helena Kennedy|Baroness Kennedy]] said \"there is a polymath quality to this man that points to someone interested in educating the whole person\"<ref>{{Citation |date = December 2005 |title = Manchester wins 'higher education institution of the year' award | journal = UniLife |publisher = The University of Manchester | location = Manchester | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages  = 3 | url=http://documents.manchester.ac.uk/display.aspx?DocID=7361 | accessdate=29 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHis brother was the historian [[Geoffrey Elton]] and he was the father of [[Ben Elton]], a comedian and author. He died in September 2018 at the age of 95.<ref>[https://www.surrey.ac.uk/news/professor-lewis-elton-remembered Professor Lewis Elton remembered]</ref>\n\n==Lewis Elton Gallery, University of Surrey==\nIn 1963 at the Surrey University Battersea campus, Elton started a project to show original artworks in the Physics Department.<ref>http://www.surrey.ac.uk/arts/visualarts/exhibitions%20and%20events/the_elton_art_collection_exhibition.htm</ref> When the University Gallery at Guildford was relocated in 1997, the gallery was dedicated to Elton and was named the [[Lewis Elton Gallery]]. The gallery hosts regular exhibitions of paintings, photographs and sculpture.\n\n==Lewis and Mary Elton Art Collection==\nThe donation of a collection of paintings and [[objets d'art]] was made to [[University of Surrey]] including works by [[Picasso]], [[Chagall]], [[Klee]] and [[Cocteau]]. The gift was marked by an exhibition at [[The Lightbox]] gallery, Woking, in January 2012.<ref>http://www.surrey.ac.uk/arts/visualarts/exhibitions%20and%20events/the_elton_art_collection_exhibition.htm</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[Ehrenberg (surname)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/calt/homepages/LewisElton.htm Biography at University College London]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060904192002/http://www.ied.edu.hk/loap/Prof_Lewis%20Elton.htm Biography at the Hong Kong Institute of Education]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051227115941/http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Units/cgjs/archive/elton_intro.shtml His family papers at Sussex University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120204164605/http://portal.surrey.ac.uk/portal/page?_pageid=887,373545&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL The Lewis Elton Gallery \u2013 old Surrey Uni website]\n*[http://www.surrey.ac.uk/arts/visualarts/lewiseltongallery/index.htm current Lewis Elton Gallery University of Surrey website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elton, Ludwig}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Surrey]]\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:English educational theorists]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English physicists]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:Jews who immigrated to the United Kingdom to escape Nazism]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rydal Penrhos]]\n[[Category:People from Prague]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00fcbingen]]\n", "name_user": "Lynettewilloughby", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added reference to Institute of eduational Technology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lewis_Elton"}
{"title_page": "Brown identity", "text_new": "'''Brown identity''' is the objective or subjective state of [[Identity (social science)|perceiving oneself]] as a [[brown person]] and as relating to being brown. The identity is subject to multiple contexts, as a part of media reporting or academic research, particularly in Asia, and the Western World.\n\n==Background==\nBrown identity has been explored academically and both discussed and reported in a a wide variety of contexts, being both an indigenous and diasporic concept,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cms.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/17/brown-and-proud-2019995.html |title=Brown and proud |author=Varsha Gowda|quote=Only during her college education did Kumar-Ratta realise that there were many different brown identities. \u201cI met Indians whose parents migrated from East-Africa, but they were Indian and this prompted me to go on a journey of discovery of my identity.\u201d|date=August 17, 2019|work=[[The New Indian Express]]}}</ref> as well as a pluralistic phenomenon with overlapping, separate, and competing sub-factors.<ref>{{cite book|author=Philip Labrado|title=Reconstructing a Brown Identity|date=2019|publisher=Floricanto Press|isbn=978-1951088057}}</ref> [[University of New Mexico]]'s Vinay Harpalani has explored the concept in depth, observing that despite variance of skin tone, whether darker or lighter, [[skin color]] gradation normally \"does not appear to play a major role for [[South Asian Americans]] claiming a Brown identity\". Despite some identification outside binaries of color, Harpalani has demonstrated how the identity does allow a distinction between certain white and black identities:<ref>{{Cite study|title=Global Perspectives on Colorism (Symposium Edition) Issue 4|author=Vinay Harpalani|page=632|chapter=To Be White, Black, or Brown? South Asian Americans and the Race-Color Distinction Race-Color Distinction|date=2015|edition=Volume 14|publisher=[[Washington University Global Studies Law Review]]}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>For  [[South  Asian Americans]], claiming Brownness allows them to establish a separate racial identity  for  themselves\u2014one  that  is  independent  of  [[White Americans|White]]  and  [[Black Americans]],  but  parallels  those  groups  by  employing  a  color-designated identity.</blockquote>\n\nDr Kumarini Silva has theorized how brownness and brown identity has, at times, even served as a cultural distraction from black-white race relations in the United States.<ref>{{Cite study|title=Brown: from identity to identification|author=Kumarini Silva|page=169|date=2010|publisher=[[Routledge]]|quote=The  vignette described  here ... is not meant to introduce blackness as part of brown identity, but rather to highlight how the particular deployment of brown as identification that is under scrutiny in this issue has in part become a way to evade the discomfort of talking  about black/white race relations in the United  States.}}</ref> Alternatively, co-authored by several academics with a range of [[ethnic minority]] backgrounds, assistant professor Fatima Zahrae Chrifi Alaoui has explored [[Arab Americans]]' connection to brown identity, theorizing how \"a Black/White binary\" can result in erasure of brownness and racial homelessness for [[brown people]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Underserved Women of Color, Voice, and Resistance: Claiming a Seat at the Table|editor1=Sonja M. Brown Givens|editor2=Keisha Edwards Tassie|chapter=My Name Is Not Maria/Samira - On the Interchangeability of Brownness in U.S. Pedagogical Contexts|author1=Fatima Z. Chrifi Alaoui|author2=Raquel Moreira|author3=Krishna Pattisapu|author4=Salma Shukri|author5=Bernadette M. Calafell|isbn=978-1498557269|date=2017|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|page=32|quote=[[Passing (racial identity)|Passing]] being forced onto a White body through the dismissal of their Brown identities also challenge identity categories through the development of a similar diasporic consciousnesses that renders them 'homeless' within Brown communities ... how a white body works to erase Brownness in a world captured within a Black/White binary ... My identity as a Brown [[Arab-American]] in white body left me feeling displaced and yearning for acceptance.}}</ref> In this regard, 2019 research by Sten Pultz Moslund - an associate professor at the [[University of Southern Denmark]] - identified separate and distinct black and brown identities emmerging in the United Kingdom; observing the societal expression of cultural difference to the white majority by [[black Britons]] and [[Asian Britons]] since 2000.<ref>{{Cite study|title=A Review of International English Literature|chapter=Postmigrant Revisions of Hybridity, Belonging, and Race in Gautam Malkani's Londonstani|author=Sten Pultz Moslund|page=107|date=2019|edition=Volume 50|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|quote=A  growing confidence in the representation of black and brown identities and  new  and  heterogeneous  ways  of  being  [[British]].  Such  confidence  is  apparent in the lack of anxieties about difference and unbelonging that characterize earlier periods of [[black British]] and [[British Asian]] literature.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSince spring 2014, [[Ontario Human Rights Commission]] director Raj Dhir has presented the ''Understanding Anti-Brown Racism'' workshop, including at institutions such as [[Humber College]]. Dhir has proposed that brown identity may be a unique phenomenon in Canada, partially resulting in distinct forms of discrimination not experienced by other minority groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humber.ca/ssaw/spring-2014/workshops/diversity-inclusion-dialogues?page=1 |title=Understanding Anti-Brown Racism |publisher=[[Humber College]]|quote=Is there a unique \u201cBrown\u201d identity in Canada? Does being \u201cBrown\u201d expose someone to different and unique forms of racism or discrimination not experienced by Black, Asian or Indigenous people?}}</ref> In 2014, Danielle Sandhu discussed the concept in ''Theorizing Brown Identity''. Sandu, a former president of the [[University of Toronto Students' Union]], analyzed the utility of brown identity by [[South Asian]] communities in Canada, and the identity's intersection with black identity; whether its expression supported or hindered the distinct separate identity of [[black people]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crrf-fcrr.ca/en/about/community/557-directions-issue-7-contributors/25981-danielle-sandhu |title=Community Network: Danielle Sandhu |quote=Her master\u2019s thesis, Theorizing Brown Identity, examines the possibilities and limitations of theorizing Brown identity as an anti-racist and anti-colonial framework ... Sandhu completed her Honours Bachelor of Science at the University of Toronto and served three terms on the executive of the University of Toronto Students\u2019 Union.|date=December 17, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Race Relations Foundation]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite study|title=Theorizing Brown Identity|author=Danielle Sandhu|location=Sociology and Equity Studies in Education|page=2-3|chapter=Introduction|date=2014|publisher=[[University of Toronto]]|quote= Brown identity or Brownness could be mobilized as an essentialist identity among South Asian communities for the purpose of shared anti-racist and anti-colonial resistance. Here Brown identity speaks to the racialized identity of South  Asians ... How does Brown identity relate to, support, or hinder the objectives of Black identity?}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Canadian writer [[Naben Ruthnum]] suggested that brown identity was at risk of being \"shaped by outside perception, by the imagination that the majority imposes upon us\".<ref name=\"globeandmail2017\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/review-naben-ruthnums-curry-explores-issues-of-identity-in-food-and-fiction/article36143189/ |title=Review: Naben Ruthnum's Curry explores issues of identity in food and fiction |author=Manisha Aggarwal-Schifellite|quote=|date=September 1, 2017|work=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> Ruthnum's writing and research into the phenomenon, which he associates with [[South Asian food]] and culture,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Curry: Eating, Reading, and Race|author=Naben Ruthnum|authorlink=Naben Ruthnum|isbn= 978-1552453513|date=2017|publisher=[[Coach House Books]]|quote=The distinctive taste of curry has often become maladroit shorthand for brown identity}}</ref> has been reviewed and explored in Canadian media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/books/how-naben-ruthnum-uses-curry-to-stir-discussion-on-what-it-means-to-be-south-asian-in-canada-1.4250265 |title=How Naben Ruthnum uses curry to stir discussion on what it means to be South Asian in Canada |author=Ryan B. Patrick |quote=His book Curry is an engaging and insightful long-form essay that connects the dots between the popular dish and how it functions as shorthand for brown identity in representing the food, culture and social perception of the [[South Asian diaspora]].|date=August 17, 2017|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref><ref name=\"globeandmail2017\" />\n\nIn 2018, discussing his experiences as a [[British Asian]], former [[featherweight]] world champion [[Naseem Hamed]] discussed the shift in brown identity and representations that occured in Britain, during the years that followed the [[9/11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/gy3z3b/how-2001-changed-everything-for-brown-identity |title=how 2001 changed everything for brown identity |author=Amna Qureshi|quote=|date=September 6, 2018|publisher=[[Vice Media]]}}</ref> Also of [[West Asian]] heritage, Dr Tufool Al-Nuaimi, an associate professor at [[Imperial College London]], has discussed the experience of being a [[Saudi American]] in the post-9/11 United States, detailing how some \"[[Arabs]] hid their brown identities behind bleached hair and blue contact lenses.\"<ref>{{Cite study|title=America's Worst Brown|author=Tufool Al-Nuaimi|location=[[MIT OpenCourseWare]]|page=8|chapter=Adopting a Different Brown|date=2005|publisher=[[MIT Press]]}}</ref>\n\nActress [[Freida Pinto]] has spoken of the importance of the identity to her with the context of [[Hollywood]], and how racial inclusivity in the industry should be meaningful, rather than what she described as token.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/2018/09/11/freida-pinto-on-woody-allen-brown-identity-in-hollywood-and-why-she-hasnt-done-a-bollywood-film-yet_a_23523586/ |title=Freida Pinto On Woody Allen, Brown Identity In Hollywood And Why She Hasn't Done A Bollywood Film Yet |author=Ankur Pathak|quote=|date=September 14, 2018|work=[[Huffington Post]]}}</ref> In 2019, musician [[Sarathy Korwar]]'s pluralistic view on the identity, within a spectrum of South Asian ethnicities, was reported in Indian media.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/dec/11/there-is-no-one-brown-identity-2074251.html |title=\u2018There is no one brown identity\u2019|author=Muneef Khan|quote=[[Sarathy Korwar]]: \"A lot of collaborators didn\u2019t reside in London but were based in Mumbai, Delhi, Abu Dhabi, etc. The idea of the album was to feature various South Asian voices to drive home the point that there is no one South Asian voice. More importantly, there is no one brown identity\"|date=December 11, 2019|work=[[The New Indian Express]]}}</ref>\n\n==Academic research==\nIn 2012, [[Douglas College]]'s Widyarini Sumartojo published research which proposed how, in an analysis of [[South Asian Canadians]] respondents, adoption of brown identity was somewhat of a counter to modern multiculturalism discourse, in that it appeared to \"re-inscribe race onto multiculturalism\".<ref>{{Cite study|title=My kind of Brown\": Indo-Canadian youth identity and belonging in Greater Vancouver|author=Sumartojo, Widyarini|page=117|chapter=Conclusion|date=2012|publisher=[[Simon Fraser University]]|quote=As a reference to skin colour, \"Brown\" seems to reflect the importance of race to respondents' identities such that its adoption stands somewhat in constrast to pervading mulitcultural discourse ... In a sense, the term \"Brown\" works to re-inscribe race onto multiculturalism}}</ref> In Ayla Raza's 2014 ''\"Negotiating \u201cBrown\u201d: Youth Identity Formations in The Greater Toronto Area'' thesis, the academic demonstrated some test participants' bias toward perceiving only those of South Asian heritage as being brown, or possessing \"an authentic \u201cBrown\u201d identity\".<ref>{{Cite study|title=\"Negotiating \u201cBrown\u201d: Youth Identity Formations in The Greater Toronto Area|author=Ayla Raza|page=48|chapter=A Brown Identity: Multi-Layered, Fluid, And Ambiguous|date=2014|publisher=[[University of Toronto]]|quote=Considered him to be \u201cBrown\u201d because he was able to trace his lineage to a country in [[South Asia]]. One of the defining features of a \u201cBrown\u201d identity, then, is the ability to trace one\u2019s lineage to South Asia. This seems to be the most salient feature of a \u201cBrown identity. \u201dHence, the theme of an authentic \u201cBrown\u201d identity, or if one is \u201creally Brown\u201d(Participant 1) arose in the interviews.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[University of North Carolina]]'s Kumarini Silva proposed how a changing understanding of brown identity had occured in the early 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wunc.org/post/being-brown-post-911-america |title=Being \u201cBrown\u201d in Post 9/11 America |author1=Anita Rao|author2=Frank Stasio|authorlink2=Frank Stasio|quote=Silva interweaves her own personal experience with ethnographic research and popular culture analysis to understand how a shifting understanding of \u201cbrown\u201d identity shapes the treatment and control of brown bodies in post-9/11 America.|date=December 8, 2016|work=[[WUNC (FM)]]}}</ref> Her book ''Brown Threat'' explores how the identity evolved into more than a political, cultural or ethnic identifier, and into an increasingly hegemonic phenomenon in the context of the [[Western world]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brown Threat: Identification in the Security State|author=Kumarini Silva|isbn= 978-1517900038|date=2016|publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]]|quote=How has the concept changed since 9/11? In the most sustained examination of these questions to date, Kumarini Silva argues that \u201cbrown\u201d is no longer conceived of solely as a cultural, ethnic, or political identity.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n*[[Cultural identity]]\n*[[Ethnic identity development]]\n*[[Ethnogenesis]]\n*[[Group identity]]\n*[[Identity (social science)]]\n*[[Identity formation]]\n*[[Identity politics]]\n*[[Self-concept]]\n*[[Social identity]]\n*[[Passing (racial identity)]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:South Asian people]]\n[[Category:West Asian people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brown identity''' is the objective or subjective state of [[Identity (social science)|perceiving oneself]] as a [[brown person]] and as relating to being brown. The identity is subject to multiple contexts, as a part of media reporting or academic research, particularly in Asia, and the Western World.\n\n==Background==\nBrown identity has been explored academically and both discussed and reported in a a wide variety of contexts, being both an indigenous and diasporic concept,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cms.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/17/brown-and-proud-2019995.html |title=Brown and proud |author=Varsha Gowda|quote=Only during her college education did Kumar-Ratta realise that there were many different brown identities. \u201cI met Indians whose parents migrated from East-Africa, but they were Indian and this prompted me to go on a journey of discovery of my identity.\u201d|date=August 17, 2019|work=[[The New Indian Express]]}}</ref> as well as a pluralistic phenomenon with overlapping, separate, and competing sub-factors.<ref>{{cite book|author=Philip Labrado|title=Reconstructing a Brown Identity|date=2019|publisher=Floricanto Press|isbn=978-1951088057}}</ref> [[University of New Mexico]]'s Vinay Harpalani has explored the concept in depth, observing that despite variance of skin tone, whether darker or lighter, [[skin color]] gradation normally \"does not appear to play a major role for [[South Asian Americans]] claiming a Brown identity\". Despite some identification outside binaries of color, Harpalani has demonstrated how the identity does allow a distinction between certain white and black identities:<ref>{{Cite study|title=Global Perspectives on Colorism (Symposium Edition) Issue 4|author=Vinay Harpalani|page=632|chapter=To Be White, Black, or Brown? South Asian Americans and the Race-Color Distinction Race-Color Distinction|date=2015|edition=Volume 14|publisher=[[Washington University Global Studies Law Review]]}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>For  [[South  Asian Americans]], claiming Brownness allows them to establish a separate racial identity  for  themselves\u2014one  that  is  independent  of  [[White Americans|White]]  and  [[Black Americans]],  but  parallels  those  groups  by  employing  a  color-designated identity.</blockquote>\n\nDr Kumarini Silva has theorized how brownness and brown identity has, at times, even served as a cultural distraction from black-white race relations in the United States.<ref>{{Cite study|title=Brown: from identity to identification|author=Kumarini Silva|page=169|date=2010|publisher=[[Routledge]]|quote=The  vignette described  here ... is not meant to introduce blackness as part of brown identity, but rather to highlight how the particular deployment of brown as identification that is under scrutiny in this issue has in part become a way to evade the discomfort of talking  about black/white race relations in the United  States.}}</ref> Alternatively, co-authored by several academics with a range of [[ethnic minority]] backgrounds, assistant professor Fatima Zahrae Chrifi Alaoui has explored [[Arab Americans]]' connection to brown identity, theorizing how \"a Black/White binary\" can result in erasure of brownness and racial homelessness for [[brown people]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Underserved Women of Color, Voice, and Resistance: Claiming a Seat at the Table|editor1=Sonja M. Brown Givens|editor2=Keisha Edwards Tassie|chapter=My Name Is Not Maria/Samira - On the Interchangeability of Brownness in U.S. Pedagogical Contexts|author1=Fatima Z. Chrifi Alaoui|author2=Raquel Moreira|author3=Krishna Pattisapu|author4=Salma Shukri|author5=Bernadette M. Calafell|isbn=978-1498557269|date=2017|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|page=32|quote=[[Passing (racial identity)|Passing]] being forced onto a White body through the dismissal of their Brown identities also challenge identity categories through the development of a similar diasporic consciousnesses that renders them 'homeless' within Brown communities ... how a white body works to erase Brownness in a world captured within a Black/White binary ... My identity as a Brown [[Arab-American]] in white body left me feeling displaced and yearning for acceptance.}}</ref> In this regard, 2019 research by Sten Pultz Moslund - an associate professor at the [[University of Southern Denmark]] - identified separate and distinct black and brown identities emmerging in the United Kingdom; observing the societal expression of cultural difference to the white majority by [[black Britons]] and [[Asian Britons]] since 2000.<ref>{{Cite study|title=A Review of International English Literature|chapter=Postmigrant Revisions of Hybridity, Belonging, and Race in Gautam Malkani's Londonstani|author=Sten Pultz Moslund|page=107|date=2019|edition=Volume 50|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|quote=A  growing confidence in the representation of black and brown identities and  new  and  heterogeneous  ways  of  being  [[British]].  Such  confidence  is  apparent in the lack of anxieties about difference and unbelonging that characterize earlier periods of [[black British]] and [[British Asian]] literature.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSince spring 2014, [[Ontario Human Rights Commission]] director Raj Dhir has presented the ''Understanding Anti-Brown Racism'' workshop, including at institutions such as [[Humber College]]. Dhir has proposed that brown identity may be a unique phenomenon in Canada, partially resulting in distinct forms of discrimination not experienced by other minority groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humber.ca/ssaw/spring-2014/workshops/diversity-inclusion-dialogues?page=1 |title=Understanding Anti-Brown Racism |publisher=[[Humber College]]|quote=Is there a unique \u201cBrown\u201d identity in Canada? Does being \u201cBrown\u201d expose someone to different and unique forms of racism or discrimination not experienced by Black, Asian or Indigenous people?}}</ref> In 2014, Danielle Sandhu discussed the concept in ''Theorizing Brown Identity''. Sandu, a former president of the [[University of Toronto Students' Union]], analyzed the utility of brown identity by [[South Asian]] communities in Canada, and the identity's intersection with black identity; whether its expression supported or hindered the distinct separate identity of [[black people]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crrf-fcrr.ca/en/about/community/557-directions-issue-7-contributors/25981-danielle-sandhu |title=Community Network: Danielle Sandhu |quote=Her master\u2019s thesis, Theorizing Brown Identity, examines the possibilities and limitations of theorizing Brown identity as an anti-racist and anti-colonial framework ... Sandhu completed her Honours Bachelor of Science at the University of Toronto and served three terms on the executive of the University of Toronto Students\u2019 Union.|date=December 17, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Race Relations Foundation]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite study|title=Theorizing Brown Identity|author=Danielle Sandhu|location=Sociology and Equity Studies in Education|page=2-3|chapter=Introduction|date=2014|publisher=[[University of Toronto]]|quote= Brown identity or Brownness could be mobilized as an essentialist identity among South Asian communities for the purpose of shared anti-racist and anti-colonial resistance. Here Brown identity speaks to the racialized identity of South  Asians ... How does Brown identity relate to, support, or hinder the objectives of Black identity?}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Canadian writer [[Naben Ruthnum]] suggested that brown identity was at risk of being \"shaped by outside perception, by the imagination that the majority imposes upon us\".<ref name=\"globeandmail2017\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/review-naben-ruthnums-curry-explores-issues-of-identity-in-food-and-fiction/article36143189/ |title=Review: Naben Ruthnum's Curry explores issues of identity in food and fiction |author=Manisha Aggarwal-Schifellite|quote=|date=September 1, 2017|work=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> Ruthnum's writing and research into the phenomenon, which he associates with [[South Asian food]] and culture,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Curry: Eating, Reading, and Race|author=Naben Ruthnum|authorlink=Naben Ruthnum|isbn= 978-1552453513|date=2017|publisher=[[Coach House Books]]|quote=The distinctive taste of curry has often become maladroit shorthand for brown identity}}</ref> has been reviewed and explored in Canadian media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/books/how-naben-ruthnum-uses-curry-to-stir-discussion-on-what-it-means-to-be-south-asian-in-canada-1.4250265 |title=How Naben Ruthnum uses curry to stir discussion on what it means to be South Asian in Canada |author=Ryan B. Patrick |quote=His book Curry is an engaging and insightful long-form essay that connects the dots between the popular dish and how it functions as shorthand for brown identity in representing the food, culture and social perception of the [[South Asian diaspora]].|date=August 17, 2017|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref><ref name=\"globeandmail2017\" />\n\nIn 2018, discussing his experiences as a [[British Asian]], former [[featherweight]] world champion [[Naseem Hamed]] discussed the shift in brown identity and representations that occured in Britain, during the years that followed the [[9/11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/gy3z3b/how-2001-changed-everything-for-brown-identity |title=how 2001 changed everything for brown identity |author=Amna Qureshi|quote=|date=September 6, 2018|publisher=[[Vice Media]]}}</ref> Also of West Asian heritage, Dr Tufool Al-Nuaimi, an associate professor at [[Imperial College London]], has discussed the experience of being a [[Saudi American]] in the post-9/11 United States, detailing how some \"[[Arabs]] hid their brown identities behind bleached hair and blue contact lenses.\"<ref>{{Cite study|title=America's Worst Brown|author=Tufool Al-Nuaimi|location=MIT OpenCourseWare|page=8|chapter=Adopting a Different Brown|date=2005|publisher=[[MIT Press]]}}</ref>\n\nActress [[Freida Pinto]] has spoken of the importance of the identity to her with the context of [[Hollywood]], and how racial inclusivity in the industry should be meaningful, rather than what she described as token.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/2018/09/11/freida-pinto-on-woody-allen-brown-identity-in-hollywood-and-why-she-hasnt-done-a-bollywood-film-yet_a_23523586/ |title=Freida Pinto On Woody Allen, Brown Identity In Hollywood And Why She Hasn't Done A Bollywood Film Yet |author=Ankur Pathak|quote=|date=September 14, 2018|work=[[Huffington Post]]}}</ref> In 2019, musician [[Sarathy Korwar]]'s pluralistic view on the identity, within a spectrum of South Asian ethnicities, was reported in Indian media.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/dec/11/there-is-no-one-brown-identity-2074251.html |title=\u2018There is no one brown identity\u2019|author=Muneef Khan|quote=[[Sarathy Korwar]]: \"A lot of collaborators didn\u2019t reside in London but were based in Mumbai, Delhi, Abu Dhabi, etc. The idea of the album was to feature various South Asian voices to drive home the point that there is no one South Asian voice. More importantly, there is no one brown identity\"|date=December 11, 2019|work=[[The New Indian Express]]}}</ref>\n\n==Academic research==\nIn 2012, [[Douglas College]]'s Widyarini Sumartojo published research which proposed how, in an analysis of [[South Asian Canadians]] respondents, adoption of brown identity was somewhat of a counter to modern multiculturalism discourse, in that it appeared to \"re-inscribe race onto multiculturalism\".<ref>{{Cite study|title=My kind of Brown\": Indo-Canadian youth identity and belonging in Greater Vancouver|author=Sumartojo, Widyarini|page=117|chapter=Conclusion|date=2012|publisher=[[Simon Fraser University]]|quote=As a reference to skin colour, \"Brown\" seems to reflect the importance of race to respondents' identities such that its adoption stands somewhat in constrast to pervading mulitcultural discourse ... In a sense, the term \"Brown\" works to re-inscribe race onto multiculturalism}}</ref> In Ayla Raza's 2014 ''\"Negotiating \u201cBrown\u201d: Youth Identity Formations in The Greater Toronto Area'' thesis, the academic demonstrated some test participants' bias toward perceiving only those of South Asian heritage as being brown, or possessing \"an authentic \u201cBrown\u201d identity\".<ref>{{Cite study|title=\"Negotiating \u201cBrown\u201d: Youth Identity Formations in The Greater Toronto Area|author=Ayla Raza|page=48|chapter=A Brown Identity: Multi-Layered, Fluid, And Ambiguous|date=2014|publisher=[[University of Toronto]]|quote=Considered him to be \u201cBrown\u201d because he was able to trace his lineage to a country in [[South Asia]]. One of the defining features of a \u201cBrown\u201d identity, then, is the ability to trace one\u2019s lineage to South Asia. This seems to be the most salient feature of a \u201cBrown identity. \u201dHence, the theme of an authentic \u201cBrown\u201d identity, or if one is \u201creally Brown\u201d(Participant 1) arose in the interviews.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[University of North Carolina]]'s Kumarini Silva proposed how a changing understanding of brown identity had occured in the early 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wunc.org/post/being-brown-post-911-america |title=Being \u201cBrown\u201d in Post 9/11 America |author1=Anita Rao|author2=Frank Stasio|authorlink2=Frank Stasio|quote=Silva interweaves her own personal experience with ethnographic research and popular culture analysis to understand how a shifting understanding of \u201cbrown\u201d identity shapes the treatment and control of brown bodies in post-9/11 America.|date=December 8, 2016|work=[[WUNC (FM)]]}}</ref> Her book ''Brown Threat'' explores how the identity evolved into more than a political, cultural or ethnic identifier, and into an increasingly hegemonic phenomenon in the context of the [[Western world]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brown Threat: Identification in the Security State|author=Kumarini Silva|isbn= 978-1517900038|date=2016|publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]]|quote=How has the concept changed since 9/11? In the most sustained examination of these questions to date, Kumarini Silva argues that \u201cbrown\u201d is no longer conceived of solely as a cultural, ethnic, or political identity.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n*[[Cultural identity]]\n*[[Ethnic identity development]]\n*[[Ethnogenesis]]\n*[[Group identity]]\n*[[Identity (social science)]]\n*[[Identity formation]]\n*[[Identity politics]]\n*[[Self-concept]]\n*[[Social identity]]\n*[[Passing (racial identity)]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:South Asian people]]\n[[Category:West Asian people]]\n", "name_user": "Peipsi-Pihkva", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:West Asian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brown_identity"}
{"title_page": "Sarah Connor (singer)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Nolting SARAH CONNOR GWO-(15 of 47).jpg\n| caption = Connor performing in 2015\n| birth_name   = Sarah Marianne Corina Lewe\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1980|06|13}}\n|birth_place =[[Delmenhorst]],<ref name=\"Birth date\">[http://www.focus.de/panorama/boulevard/entertainment-von-niedersachsen-nach-new-york_aid_205335.html FOCUS Magazin | Nr. 3 (2002)] (German)</ref> [[West Germany]]\n| years_active = 2000\u2013present\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter\n*dancer}}\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Marc Terenzi]]|2004|2008|reason=div}}\n| partner         = Florian Fischer (2011\u2013present)\n| children     = 4\n| label =<!-- [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]-->\n| website = {{URL|http://sarah-connor.com/}}\n}}\n'''Sarah Connor''' (born '''Sarah Marianne Corina Lewe'''; June 13, 1980) is an American-German singer, songwriter, and dancer. Raised in [[Delmenhorst]], she became part of a [[church choir]] at the age of six. Connor rose to prominence after she signed with X-Cell Records in 2000 and released her debut album ''[[Green Eyed Soul]]'' (2001) the following year. She followed it with a series of successful albums, including ''[[Unbelievable (Sarah Connor album)|Unbelievable]]'' (2002), ''[[Key to My Soul]]'' (2003), ''[[Naughty but Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice]]'' (2005), ''[[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor album)|Christmas in My Heart]]'' (2005), ''[[Soulicious (Sarah Connor album)|Soulicious]]'' (2007), ''[[Sexy as Hell]]'' (2008) and ''[[Real Love (Sarah Connor album)|Real Love]]'' (2010). Several songs from these albums became hit singles on the pop record charts, including the number-one hits \"[[From Sarah with Love]]\", \"[[Music is the Key]]\", \"[[Just One Last Dance]]\", \"[[Living to Love You]]\" and \"[[From Zero to Hero]]\". In 2015, Connor's first German language project ''[[Muttersprache (album)|Muttersprache]]'' became her second chart topper after a decade.\n\nHer popularity was further enhanced by the [[ProSieben]] reality television series ''[[Sarah & Marc in Love]]'' (2005) and ''[[Sarah & Marc in Love|Sarah & Marc Crazy in Love]]'' (2008) alongside her then-husband [[Marc Terenzi]], chronicling their marriage and careers. In 2010, she returned to television to become a judge on the debut season of the German ''[[X Factor (German TV series)|X Factor]]'' adaptation of which she remained part for two further seasons. In 2014, she joined the cast of the debut season of ''[[Sing meinen Song \u2013 Das Tauschkonzert]]'', the German version of the series ''[[The Best Singers (series)|The Best Singers]]'' whose accompanying compilation album topped the [[Austrian Albums Chart|Austrian]] and [[German Albums Chart]]. The following year, she served as a guest coach on the [[RTL II]] remake of the talent series ''[[Popstars 2015]]''.\n\nConnor has sold seven million albums worldwide and is recognized as one of the most successful German vocalists to emerge in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universal-music.de/sarah-connor/biografie|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 Universal Music Group|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> According to [[GfK Entertainment]], she is the first recording act to ever have scored four consecutive chart-topping hits on the [[Media Control Charts|German Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Yvonne|last=Beister|title=Zum 30. Geburtstag Ein TV-Comeback|publisher=Stuttgarter-Nachrichten.de|url=http://www.stuttgarter-nachrichten.de/inhalt.sarah-connor-zum-30-geburtstag-ein-tv-comeback.51ce6d0e-a60d-402d-8a4d-9803a09fcf4c.html|date=September 12, 2010|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> In 2017, [[Deutsche Welle]] ranked her third on its list of the top ten German solo acts who have enjoyed international success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ranking: Die 10 erfolgreichsten deutschen S\u00e4ngerinnen und S\u00e4nger|publisher=[[DW.com]]|url=https://www.dw.com/de/ranking-die-10-erfolgreichsten-deutschen-s%C3%A4ngerinnen-und-s%C3%A4nger/g-19420855|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref> A 13-time nominee, Connor won two [[Echo Music Prize]] and has been the recipient of four [[:de:Comet (Musikpreis)|Comet]]s, a [[Top of the Pops|Top of the Pops Award]], a [[Goldene Kamera]], a [[Goldene Europa]], and a [[World Music Award]]. Separated from Terenzi, father of her first two children, Connor has been in a relationship with her manager [[The Boyz (German musical group)|Florian Fischer]] since 2010. The couple have another two children of their own.\n\n==Early life==\nConnor is the eldest of six siblings born to Michael Lewe, a [[copywriter]] from [[New Orleans]], and his wife Soraya Lewe-Tacke (n\u00e9e Gray), a former fashion model and homemaker of [[Scottish people|Scottish]], Irish, and German descent, in [[Hamburg]].<ref name=\"focus2002\">{{cite web|title=Von Niedersachsen nach New York|website=[[Focus.de]]|url=http://www.focus.de/panorama/boulevard/entertainment-von-niedersachsen-nach-new-york_aid_205335.html|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> She has four sisters, including [[Bushido (rapper)#Personal life|Anna-Maria Lagerblom]], the wife of German rapper [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]], as well as Marisa, Sophia-Luisa, and Valentina; and one brother, Robin.<ref name=\"vf\">{{cite web|last=Jessen|first=Philipp|date=April 5, 2007|title=Sarah Connor: Das nackte Leben|work=Vanity Fair Magazine|url=http://www2.vanityfair.de/articles/leute/sarah-connor/2007/04/05/1/00236/|accessdate=2007-06-12 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070515180119/http://www.vanityfair.de/articles/leute/sarah-connor/2007/04/05/1/00236/ |archivedate = May 15, 2007}}</ref> Her maternal half-brothers Mick and Lex were born in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connors Mutter bekommt Zwillinge|website=[[Welt.de]]|url=https://www.welt.de/vermischtes/article2045523/Sarah_Connors_Mutter_bekommt_Zwillinge.html|accessdate=2008-06-19}}</ref> Connor grew up listening to [[soul music]], mostly influenced by her paternal grandfather, a former jazz and R&B [[pianist]] from [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> A church choir provided her with her first experience in [[gospel music]] at the age of six.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> In 1989, the family relocated from [[Hamburg]] to [[Delmenhorst]], where Connor attended the Max-Planck-Gymnasium (high school).<ref name=\"weser2015\">{{cite web|first=Uwe|last=Dammann|title=Doppeltes Heimspiel f\u00fcr Sarah Connor|website=Weser-Kurier.de|url=https://www.weser-kurier.de/bremen/bremen-kultur_artikel,-Doppeltes-Heimspiel-fuer-Sarah-Connor-_arid,1162402.html|date=July 8, 2015|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> She also enrolled at the local performing arts school, where she received dancing, singing, and acting lessons, which she paid for through [[waitressing]] and modelling jobs.<ref name=\"weser2015\"/> After dropping out of school, she completed an internship with [[RTL Television]].<ref name=\"weser2015\"/>\n\nIn 1997, Connor and her sister Anna-Maria were picked to sing with the [[backing singer|backing choir]] during the performances of \"[[Earth Song]]\" and \"[[Heal the World]]\" at [[Michael Jackson]]'s [[HIStory World Tour]] in [[Bremen]], Germany.<ref name=\"vf\"/> Overwhelmed by a personal meeting with Jackson at the end of the show,<ref name=\"vf\"/> she began to record a number of demo tapes under the pseudonym ''Sarah Gray'',<ref name=\"ym\">{{cite web|last=Bonacich|first=Drago|title=Sarah Connors \u2013 Biography|work=Yahoo! Music|url=http://music.yahoo.com/ar-305393-bio--Sarah-Connor|accessdate=2008-06-21}}</ref> including [[cover version]]s such as \"[[Silent Night]]\" and \"[[This Christmas (Donnie Hathaway song)|This Christmas]]\" as well as the local radio success \"Ula la Ula.\"<ref name=\"delorado\">{{cite web|date=August 11, 2005 |title=Sarah Connors Weg zum Erfolg |work=Delorado |url=http://www.deldorado.borgmeier-media.de/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=33&Itemid=33 |accessdate=2008-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517165250/http://www.deldorado.borgmeier-media.de/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=33&Itemid=33 |archivedate=May 17, 2007 }}</ref> In 1998, her boyfriend Martin Scholz, member of the boy band [[Touch\u00e9 (band)|Touch\u00e9]], arranged for Connor to sign a management deal with the group's manager.<ref name=\"delorado\"/> She subsequently served as their opening act for a [[Bremen]] concert in July 1998.<ref name=\"weser2015\"/> Unhappy with her management though, Connor transitioned to the manager Carlo Vista and began work on the single \"This Christmas\" with the producers Oliver Hintz and Thomas N\u00f6hre. It was released through Villa Records in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Gray \u2013 This Christmas|website=[[Discogs]].com|url=https://www.discogs.com/de/Sarah-Gray-This-Christmas/release/7576366|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> Also that year, she provided the leading vocals for the German producer Marc van Linden's [[trance music|trance]] remix of the 1982 record \"[[The Last Unicorn (soundtrack)|Last Unicorn]]\", which reached number eighty-six on the [[German Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marc van Linden - The Last Unicorn|website=AustrianCharts.at|url=https://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Marc+van+Linden&titel=The+Last+Unicorn&cat=s|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> In 2000, music manager [[George Glueck]] eventually signed her as ''Sarah Connor'' with the [[Sony]] subsidiary X-Cell Records.<ref name=\"delorado\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===2001\u20132003: Breakthrough with ''From Sarah With Love''===\nConnor fluctuated between Berlin, [[Hamburg]], and [[Hannover]] to work on her [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[hip hop]]-driven debut album, involving German music producers B\u00fclent Aris, Rob Tyger and Kay Denar as well as international collaborators such as [[Kwasi Jones Martin|Eddie Martin]] and rapper [[TQ (singer)|TQ]].<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Its release was preceded by the top five and top 20 hit singles \"[[Let's Get Back to Bed \u2013 Boy!]]\" and \"[[French Kissing]]\", respectively, as well as her breakthrough hit, the ballad \"[[From Sarah with Love]]\", which reached the top position in Germany, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland and raised Connor's fame all over Europe.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Eventually released in November 2001, ''[[Green Eyed Soul (Sarah Connor album)|Green Eyed Soul]]'' generally mixed reception from music critics, who declared it a mixed bag but considered it a solid career launcher.<ref name=\"laut.de\">{{cite web |last=Fr\u00f6mmer |first=Michael |url=http://www.laut.de/lautstark/cd-reviews/c/connor_sarah/green_eyed_soul/index.htm |title=G\u00e4ngige R'n'B Grooves, zeitgem\u00e4\u00dfe Hip Hop-Muster, Pop Beats \u00e0 la Britney|language=German |publisher=laut.de |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> The album debuted at number two on the [[Media Control Charts|German Albums Chart]], and charted within the top five in Austria, Finland and Switzerland, reaching gold status in Austria, Czech, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland, while earning platinum certifications in Finland and Germany.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Connor was subsequently awarded a [[Goldene Europa]] and won the [[Echo Music Prize|Echo Music Prize for Best National Rock/Pop Female Artist]], among three nominations.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/>\n\n[[File:Sarah Connor 4.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Connor in 2002 at ''[[Verstehen Sie Spa\u00df?]]'']] The following year, Connor embarked on the Green Eyed Soul Tour in 2002 and began production on her second studio album ''[[Unbelievable (Sarah Connor album)|Unbelievable]]''. A continuation of ''Green Eyed Soul'', she reteamed with Aris, Denar and Tyger to work on the majority of the album, with American musicians [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Jerry Duplessis]], and [[Diane Warren]] also joining the project.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Jean wrote, produced and rapped on the album's [[lead single]], \"[[One Nite Stand (of Wolves and Sheep)]]\", which once again entered the top 5. ''Unbelievable'' simultaneously achieved gold status in Germany within 48 hours and spawned another three singles, including \"[[Skin on Skin (Sarah Connor song)|Skin on Skin]]\", \"[[He's Unbelievable]]\" and \"[[Bounce (Sarah Connor Song)|Bounce]]\".\n\nIn October 2003, Connor released a live DVD branded ''Sarah Connor Live \u2013 [[A Night to Remember: Pop Meets Classic]]'', whose performance had been recorded at the Alten Kasselhaus in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] on January 24, including individual performances of own songs with a classical orchestra backing her up. In November 2003, in spite of being heavily pregnant with her first child, Connor released her third album called, ''[[Key to My Soul]]''. The album's first single, \"[[Music Is the Key]]\" featuring New York [[a cappella]] singers [[Naturally 7]], became her second number-one hit in Germany. \"[[Just One Last Dance]]\", the album's second and final single, was a re-recorded edition of the album's original version, including new vocals by Marc Terenzi's band [[Natural (band)|Natural]]. The duet once again reached number-one in Austria, Germany, and Switzerland and the top 20 on a composite World Top 40.\n\nThe album ''[[Sarah Connor (album)|Sarah Connor]]'' featured the first single, \"Bounce\". It was released in many countries, including Japan, Australia, New Zealand, Canada and the United States. In Germany, the single made it to #14 on the charts. In England and Ireland it peaked at number 14 and was certified gold in Australia.  In America, the song only managed a #54 on the Billboard Hot 100.  The album made it to number 106 and took off in the U.S., selling almost 100.000 copies.\n\n===2004\u20132008: International success===\nAfter a lengthy hiatus that saw the birth of her son Tyler, Connor returned to music in fall 2004 with the release of her single \"[[Living to Love You]].\" The ballad reached number-one in Germany and Switzerland, becoming her third consecutive chart-topper, and preceded her fourth album ''[[Naughty But Nice (album)|Naughty But Nice]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 Living To Love You|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/3226|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Connor re-teamed with longtime contributors Booya, Kay Denar und Rob Tyger to work on the album, whose release coincided with the \nbroadcast of her [[ProSieben]] reality series ''[[Sarah & Marc in Love]]''. Her highest-charting effort yet, ''Naughty But Nice'' debuted on top of the German Albums Chart and reached the top three in Austria and Switzerland, selling 100,000 copies within the first two days of its release.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 ''Naughty But Nice'' |publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/album/18027|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Critical reaction towards the album was generally mixed, with [[Allmusic]] rating it three starts out of five,<ref>{{cite web|title=''Naughty but Nice'' review|website=[[Allmusic]]|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r740510|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> and ''laut.de'' summing it as \"underclass music for the disco around the corner.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Schuh|title=Unterschichtenmusik F\u00fcr Die Dorfdisco Um Die Ecke|publisher=laut.de|url=http://www.laut.de/Sarah-Connor/Naughty-But-Nice-(Album)|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Spawning just one another single, \"[[From Zero to Hero]]\" was picked to be used as the theme song to the [[computer-animated]] movie ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' (2005),The song became her fifth chart-topping single in Germany and the fourth number-one hit single in a row.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 From Zero To Hero|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/3300|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SarahConnorEinZuhausef\u00fcrKinder.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Connor performing live in 2008]]\nIn fall 2005, Connor embarked on the [[Naughty But Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice concert tour]]. Compiling twenty-three dates in Austria, Germany and Switzerland, the tour concluded a month later. In December 2005, she released a [[holiday album]] named ''[[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor album)|Christmas in My Heart]]''. Containing a mix of traditional but contemporary English standards and re-written German songs in English language, both the album and its [[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor song)|same-titled lead single]] reached number four on the charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 ''Christmas in My Heart''|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/album/18170|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'Christmas in My Heart'|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/7345|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Eventually certified platinum by the [[IFPI]],<ref name=\"cert\">{{cite certification|region=Germany|artist=Sarah Connor|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> the album was re-released the following year, including the previously unreleased single \"[[The Best Side of Life]],\" another top four success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'The Best Side of Life'|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/11581|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref>\n\nReturning from yet another hiatus after the birth of her daughter Summer in 2006, Connor released her sixth studio album ''[[Soulicious (Sarah Connor album)|Soulicious]]'' in March 2007. Mainly made up of 1960s and 70s [[Motown]] covers, but also including two original songs, recording for the entire album took place at the former main building of the [[Berliner Rundfunk]], where Connor was backed by a symphonic orchestra of forty-eight musicians.<ref>{{cite web|title=Information on ''Soulicious''|publisher=SarahConnor.com|url=http://www.sarah-connor.com/de/media/discography/album/soulicious.html|accessdate=2010-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107185321/http://www.sarah-connor.com/de/media/discography/album/soulicious.html|archivedate=2011-01-07}}</ref> Upon its release, the album reached the top ten in Austria, Germany and Switzerland, where it each reached gold status.<ref name=\"cert\"/> Critics, again, gave ''Soulicious'' a mixed response, with ''CDStarts.de'' calling it \"a sterile soul adaption for ''[[The Dome (television program)|The Dome]]'' stage.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Matthias|last=Reichel|title=''Soulicious'' Review|publisher=CDStarts.de|url=http://www.cdstarts.de/kritiken/88956-Soulicious.html|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Leading single \"[[The Impossible Dream (The Quest)]],\" which was featured in a publicity campaign for the comeback fight of German [[Boxing|boxer]] [[Henry Maske]], and \"[[Sexual Healing#Sarah Connor version|Sexual Healing]],\" a duet with American singer [[Ne-Yo]], reached the top ten and top twenty of the singles charts respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'The Impossible Dream '|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/12488|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor and Ne-Yo \u2013 'Sexual Healing'|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/26859|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref>\n\nHeading into a new musical direction, Connor intensified work on her next original album with producers such as [[Remee]], [[Thomas Troelsen]] and [[J. R. Rotem]]. In May 2008, it was announced Connor and her family would once again participate in an eight-part reality show titled ''Sarah and Marc: Still Crazy in Love\"'' on [[ProSieben]]. The special began airing on July 3, 2008, and followed the recording and promotional events for the new album, branded ''[[Sexy as Hell]]''.<ref>[http://www.prosieben.de/music_cd/samil/artikel/52525/ TV: Serien & Sendungen von ProSieben]. Prosieben.de. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080601073820/http://unterhaltung.de.msn.com/stars/news-artikel.aspx?cp-documentid=8346012 Sarah und Marc mit neuer Liebesdoku]. MSN.com (in German). May 21, 2008</ref> Its first single, \"[[Under My Skin (Sarah Connor song)|Under My Skin]],\" co-written by Troelsen, was released on August 1, 2008, in [[German-speaking Europe]], with the album following on August 22, 2008. Subsequently, she was nominated for an ECHO.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n===2009\u2013present: ''X-Factor'', ''Real Love'' and ''Muttersprache''===\n[[File:Sarah Connor Bremen1.jpg|thumbnail|Sarah Connor performing at the Muttersprache Tour in March 2016]]\nIn 2009, Connor contributed to a re-recorded version of [[Enrique Iglesias]]' duet \"[[Takin' Back My Love]],\" replacing American singer [[Ciara]]'s original vocals on the song. Released as the second single from Iglesias' 2008 ''[[Greatest Hits (Enrique Iglesias album)|Greatest Hits]]'' album in [[German-speaking Europe]], Poland and the [[Czech Republic]], it reached the top ten of the German Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enrique Iglesias and Sarah Connor \u2013 Takin Back My Love |publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/43299|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> In April 2010, it was announced that Connor would appear alongside mentor George Glueck and musician [[Till Br\u00f6nner]] as a judge on the debut series of ''[[X Factor (Germany)|X Factor]]'', broadcast on the German [[VOX (German TV channel)|VOX]] network.<ref name=\"gala\">[http://www.gala.de/stars/news/96648/Sarah-Connor-Jurorin-bei-X-Factor.html Sarah Connor: Jurorin bei \"X Factor\" \u2013 News auf]. Gala.de. March 8, 2010. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> Connor was given the 16-24s category (made up of solo contestants between 16 and 24) but failed to reach the final show when her contestant [[Mati Gavriel]] was eliminated in his seventh week and [[Edita Abdieski]] was crowned the winner of ''X Factor'' instead.<ref name=\"gala\"/> Amid her appearances on ''X Factor'', Connor released her eighth studio album ''[[Real Love (Sarah Connor album)|Real Love]]'' on October 22, 2010. It earned a lukewarm reception by critics,<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah-Nina|last=Rademacher|url=http://www.laut.de/Sarah-Connor/Real-Love-(Album)|title=Sarah, du hast den X-Factor ...|accessdate=2010-11-06|work=laut.de}}</ref> and debuted at number eight on the [[German Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"acharts\">{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/album/58333|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 ''Real Love'' Music Charts |accessdate=2010-11-06|work=\u03b1Charts.us}}</ref> Altogether, ''Real Love'' produced two singles, including \"[[Cold as Ice (Sarah Connor song)|Cold as Ice]],\" which reached the top twenty on the [[German Singles Chart]], and its [[Real Love (Sarah Connor song)|title track]], both of which became her lowest-charting singles in years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/song/58072|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'Cold As Ice' Music Charts |accessdate=2010-11-06|work=\u03b1Charts.us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beatblogger.de/vo-vorschau/|title=V\u00d6-Vorschau|accessdate=2010-11-06|work=Beatblogger.de}}</ref> Connor returned for the second and third ''X Factor'' series in 2011 and 2012 and was given the groups and over 25s categories, respecitvely. Again, her contestants Nica & Joe and Bj\u00f6rn Paulsen each placed third, losing to [[David Pfeffer]] and [[Mrs. Greenbird]].<ref name=\"gala\"/>\n\nFollowing a hiatus, in 2014, Connor appeared in the reality television series ''[[Sing meinen Song - Das Tauschkonzert]]'', the German version of ''[[The Best Singers (series)|The Best Singers]]'' series. In 2015, Connor released her ninth studio album ''[[Muttersprache (album)|Muttersprache]]'', her first album to be entirely recorded in [[German language|German]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite web|date=2006-02-01|title=Muttersprache (Deluxe Version)|publisher=Play.Google.de|url=https://play.google.com/store/music/album/Sarah_Connor_Muttersprache_Deluxe_Version?id=Byjmelola4mbdegqtkjif6zbom4&PAffiliateID=11lxBw|accessdate=2015-04-20}}</ref> Encouraged to record songs in her native language, following her performances on ''Sing meinen Song'', Connor worked with a smaller range of producers on the album, including Daniel Faust, [[Peter Plate]], and Ulf Leo Sommer. Upon its release, ''Muttersprache'' debuted on top of on the [[GfK Entertainment|German Albums Chart]], becoming her second number-one album following 2005's ''[[Naughty but Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice]]''. With first week sales of more than 100,000 copies in Germany, ''Muttersprache'' was certified [[List of music recording certifications|gold]] by the [[Bundesverband Musikindustrie]] (BVMI) just days after its release.<ref name=\"pp\">{{cite web|date=2006-06-03|title=SARAH CONNOR: Platz #1 in den Offiziellen Deutschen Albumcharts|publisher=Presseportal|url=http://www.presseportal.de/pm/58621/3038018|accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref> It has since been certified [[List of music recording certifications|platinum]].<ref name=\"uv\">{{cite web|title=Universal-Vertriebstagung 2015 \u2013 Briegmann: \"Wachstum ohne Streaming ist nicht denkbar\"|publisher=Musikmarkt.de|url=http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|accessdate=2015-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019032132/http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|archive-date=October 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album also debuted at number-one on the [[Swiss Albums Chart]], her first album to do so.<ref name=\"pp\"/> \"[[Wie sch\u00f6n du bist]]\" became Connor's highest-charting single in a decade, reaching number two on the [[German Singles Chart]], and sold over 260,000 copies.<ref name=\"uv\">{{cite web|title=Universal-Vertriebstagung 2015 \u2013 Briegmann: \"Wachstum ohne Streaming ist nicht denkbar\"|publisher=Musikmarkt.de|url=http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|accessdate=2015-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019032132/http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|archive-date=October 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nConnor met [[Marc Terenzi]], the lead singer of American boy band [[Natural (band)|Natural]], at the Bravo Happy Holidays festival in [[Rust, Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|Rust]], Germany in July 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor Und Marc Terenzi Gmeinsam Im Exklusiven Interview|url=http://www.presseportal.de/pm/13440/373742/bravo|date=August 20, 2002|work=BRAVO|publisher=Presseportal.de|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> The pair began dating and in June 2003, it was announced they were engaged and expecting their first child, Tyler Marc Terenzi, who was born on February 2, 2004 in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Popstar-Liebe: Sarah Connor Ist Mutter|url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/0,1518,284737,00.html|magazine=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=March 2, 2004|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> On February 29, 2004 the couple invited their friends to a dinner supposedly to celebrate the birth of their son; however they announced that they in fact had eloped. The couple renewed their vows this time with a wedding ceremony on August 18, 2005 in Altafulla, [[Tarragon\u00e8s]], near [[Barcelona, Spain]]. The wedding was the subject of their ProSieben reality show ''[[Sarah and Marc in Love]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor (24) \u2013 Ein Pop-Produkt Wird Besichtigt|url=http://www.dk-online.de/Nachrichten/Archiv/index.csp?artikel=784027|publisher=DK-Online.de|date=May 5, 2005|accessdate=2010-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718231933/http://www.dk-online.de/Nachrichten/Archiv/index.csp?artikel=784027|archivedate=July 18, 2011}}</ref> On June 23, 2006, Connor gave birth to their second child, a girl, named Summer Antonia Soraya.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Herzfehler \u2013 Sarah Connor Bangt Um Tochter|url=http://www.stern.de/lifestyle/leute/herzfehler-sarah-connor-bangt-um-tochter-564391.html|magazine=[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]]|date=June 19, 2006|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> In November 2008, Connor announced her separation from Terenzi.\n\nIn April 2010, Connor announced that she is in a relationship with her manager, Florian Fischer, the singer of the 1990s pop group The Boyz.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor Ist Nach Scheidung Wieder Liiert|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/vermischtes/article1673152/Sarah-Connor-ist-nach-Scheidung-wieder-liiert.html|date=October 24, 2010|work=[[Hamburger Abendblatt]]|publisher=Abendblatt.de|accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref> In February 2011, the two confirmed that they were expecting a child.<ref>{{in lang|de}} [http://www.bild.de/BILD/unterhaltung/leute/2011/02/21/sarah-connor/im-vierten-monat-schwanger-baby-mit-florian-fischer.html Pop-S\u00e4ngerin freut sich auf ihr 3. Baby: Sarah Connor im 4. Monat schwanger \u2013 Leute]. Bild.de. February 21, 2011. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> Their daughter Delphine Malou was born in September 2011. They welcomed their son Jax Llewyn in January 2017.<ref>http://www.zeit.de/news/2017-01/18/leute-sarah-connor-bringt-soehnchen-jax-llewyn-zur-welt-18072008</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sarah Connor discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Green Eyed Soul]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Unbelievable (Sarah Connor album)|Unbelievable]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Key to My Soul]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Naughty but Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor album)|Christmas in My Heart]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Soulicious (Sarah Connor album)|Soulicious]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Sexy as Hell]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Real Love (Sarah Connor album)|Real Love]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Muttersprache (album)|Muttersprache]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Herz Kraft Werke]]'' (2019)\n\n==Tours==\n* Green Eyed Soul Tour (2002)\n* Sarah Connor Live (2003\u20132004)\n* Naughty but Nice Tour (2005)\n* Sexy as Hell Tour (2009)\n* Sarah Connor China Tour (Beijing/Guangzhou) (2010\u20132012)\n* Christmas in My Heart Live (2012\u20132013)\n* Muttersprache Live (2015\u20132017)\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=4 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Television guest appearances\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Role\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| \"[[Sarah & Marc in Love]]\"\n| Herself\n| Reality Television\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"[[Sarah & Marc Crazy in Love]]\"\n| Herself\n| Reality Television, Promo for ''[[Sexy as Hell]]''\n|-\n|2009\n|Leo Piepmatz rockt das Haus: Eine Mut-Mach-Geschichte f\u00fcr kleine L\u00f6wen und gro\u00dfe Rockstars\n| Herself\n| Audiobook \n|-\n| 2010\u20132012\n| \"[[The X Factor (UK)|X-Factor]]\"\n| Herself\n| Main juror\n|-\n|2014\n| [[Sing meinen Song - Das Tauschkonzert]]\n| Herself\n| Television Music Show by VOX <br> Season 1\n|-\n|2014\n| [[Sing meinen Song - Das Tauschkonzert]] (Das Weihnachtskonzert) \n|Herself\n| Television Music Show by VOX <br> Season 1 <br> The Christmas Conzert\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* '''1Live Krone'''\n** 2005 \u2013 Best Female Artist\n* '''Antville Music Video Awards'''\n** 2005 - Worst Video (\"Christmas in My Heart\") \u2013 ''nominated'' \n* '''BMI Pop Awards'''\n** 2005 - Pop Award (\"Bounce\") - '''WON'''\n* '''Bravo Otto'''\n** 2001 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 Silver\n** 2003 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 Bronze\n** 2004 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 GOLD\n** 2005 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 GOLD\n** 2006 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 GOLD\n** 2007 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 Bronze\n** 2008 \u2013 Female Singer \u2013 GOLD\n* '''Comet'''\n** 2001 \u2013 Best National Newcomer\n** 2005 \u2013 Best Female Artist\n** 2007 \u2013 Best Female Artist\n** 2009 \u2013 Best Female Artist\n* '''[[DIVA (music award)|DIVA-Award]]'''\n** 2005 \u2013 Music Artist of the Year\n* '''[[ECHO (music award)|ECHO]]''' (''including nominations'')\n** 2002 \u2013 Best National Newcomer (''Green Eyed Soul'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2002 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Green Eyed Soul'') \u2013 '''WON'''\n** 2002 \u2013 Best National Single \u2013 From Sarah with Love \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2003 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Unbelievable'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2004 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Key to My Soul'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2006 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Naughty But Nice'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2007 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Christmas in my Heart'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2008 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Soulicious'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2009 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Sexy as Hell'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2011 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Real Love'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2015 \u2013 Partner of the Year (''Sing meinen Song'') \u2013 '''WON'''\n** 2016 \u2013 Best National Female Pop/Rock Artist (''Muttersprache'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n** 2016 \u2013 Album of the Year (''Muttersprache'') \u2013 ''nominated''\n* '''[[Goldene Europa]]'''\n** 2002 \u2013 Most Successful German Female Singer\n* '''[[Goldene Kamera]]'''\n** 2005 \u2013 Pop National\n* '''MAXIM'''\n** 2002 \u2013 Woman of the Year \u2013 Pop Star\n* '''Neo Award'''\n** 2004 \u2013 Most Downloaded Album \u2013 Key to My Soul\n* '''Radio Regenbogen Award'''\n** 2002 \u2013 Best Hit 2001 \u2013 From Sarah with Love\n* '''[[Top of the Pops]] Award'''\n** 2001 Best German Newcomer\n* '''[[World Music Awards|World Music Award]]'''\n** 2004 \u2013 Best Selling German Artist\n* '''World of Music Award'''\n** 2008 \u2013 Best National Female Artist\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sarah Connor}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.sarah-connor.com}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928141156/http://www.sarahconnor.org/discography/ Complete discography page]\n\n{{Sarah Connor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Connor, Sarah}}\n[[Category:Sarah Connor (singer)| ]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:German people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Germany]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of Germany]]\n[[Category:German soul singers]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:German people of American descent]]\n[[Category:German female pop singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Nolting SARAH CONNOR GWO-(15 of 47).jpg\n| caption = Connor performing in 2015\n| birth_name   = Sarah Marianne Corina Lewe\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1980|06|13}}\n|birth_place =[[Delmenhorst]],<ref name=\"Birth date\">[http://www.focus.de/panorama/boulevard/entertainment-von-niedersachsen-nach-new-york_aid_205335.html FOCUS Magazin | Nr. 3 (2002)] (German)</ref> [[West Germany]]\n| years_active = 2000\u2013present\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter\n*dancer}}\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Marc Terenzi]]|2004|2008|reason=div}}\n| partner         = Florian Fischer (2011\u2013present)\n| children     = 4\n| label =<!-- [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]-->\n| website = {{URL|http://sarah-connor.com/}}\n}}\n'''Sarah Connor''' (born '''Sarah Marianne Corina Lewe'''; June 13, 1980) is an American-German singer, songwriter, and dancer. Raised in [[Delmenhorst]], she became part of a [[church choir]] at the age of six. Connor rose to prominence after she signed with X-Cell Records in 2000 and released her debut album ''[[Green Eyed Soul]]'' (2001) the following year. She followed it with a series of successful albums, including ''[[Unbelievable (Sarah Connor album)|Unbelievable]]'' (2002), ''[[Key to My Soul]]'' (2003), ''[[Naughty but Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice]]'' (2005), ''[[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor album)|Christmas in My Heart]]'' (2005), ''[[Soulicious (Sarah Connor album)|Soulicious]]'' (2007), ''[[Sexy as Hell]]'' (2008) and ''[[Real Love (Sarah Connor album)|Real Love]]'' (2010). Several songs from these albums became hit singles on the pop record charts, including the number-one hits \"[[From Sarah with Love]]\", \"[[Music is the Key]]\", \"[[Just One Last Dance]]\", \"[[Living to Love You]]\" and \"[[From Zero to Hero]]\". In 2015, Connor's first German language project ''[[Muttersprache (album)|Muttersprache]]'' became her second chart topper after a decade.\n\nHer popularity was further enhanced by the [[ProSieben]] reality television series ''[[Sarah & Marc in Love]]'' (2005) and ''[[Sarah & Marc in Love|Sarah & Marc Crazy in Love]]'' (2008) alongside her then-husband [[Marc Terenzi]], chronicling their marriage and careers. In 2010, she returned to television to become a judge on the debut season of the German ''[[X Factor (German TV series)|X Factor]]'' adaptation of which she remained part for two further seasons. In 2014, she joined the cast of the debut season of ''[[Sing meinen Song \u2013 Das Tauschkonzert]]'', the German version of the series ''[[The Best Singers (series)|The Best Singers]]'' whose accompanying compilation album topped the [[Austrian Albums Chart|Austrian]] and [[German Albums Chart]]. The following year, she served as a guest coach on the [[RTL II]] remake of the talent series ''[[Popstars 2015]]''.\n\nConnor has sold seven million albums worldwide and is recognized as one of the most successful German vocalists to emerge in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universal-music.de/sarah-connor/biografie|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 Universal Music Group|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> According to [[GfK Entertainment]], she is the first recording act to ever have scored four consecutive chart-topping hits on the [[Media Control Charts|German Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Yvonne|last=Beister|title=Zum 30. Geburtstag Ein TV-Comeback|publisher=Stuttgarter-Nachrichten.de|url=http://www.stuttgarter-nachrichten.de/inhalt.sarah-connor-zum-30-geburtstag-ein-tv-comeback.51ce6d0e-a60d-402d-8a4d-9803a09fcf4c.html|date=September 12, 2010|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> In 2017, [[Deutsche Welle]] ranked her third on its list of the top ten German solo acts who have enjoyed international success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ranking: Die 10 erfolgreichsten deutschen S\u00e4ngerinnen und S\u00e4nger|publisher=[[DW.com]]|url=https://www.dw.com/de/ranking-die-10-erfolgreichsten-deutschen-s%C3%A4ngerinnen-und-s%C3%A4nger/g-19420855|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref> A 13-time nominee, Connor won two [[Echo Music Prize]] and has been the recipient of four [[:de:Comet (Musikpreis)|Comet]]s, a [[Top of the Pops|Top of the Pops Award]], a [[Goldene Kamera]], a [[Goldene Europa]], and a [[World Music Award]]. Separated from Terenzi, father of her first two children, Connor has been in a relationship with her manager [[The Boyz (German musical group)|Florian Fischer]] since 2010. The couple have another two children of their own.\n\n==Early life==\nConnor is the eldest of six siblings born to Michael Lewe, a [[copywriter]] from [[New Orleans]], and his wife Soraya Lewe-Tacke (n\u00e9e Gray), a former fashion model and homemaker of [[Scottish people|Scottish]], Irish, and German descent, in [[Hamburg]].<ref name=\"focus2002\">{{cite web|title=Von Niedersachsen nach New York|website=[[Focus.de]]|url=http://www.focus.de/panorama/boulevard/entertainment-von-niedersachsen-nach-new-york_aid_205335.html|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> She has four sisters, including [[Bushido (rapper)#Personal life|Anna-Maria Lagerblom]], the wife of German rapper [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]], as well as Marisa, Sophia-Luisa, and Valentina; and one brother, Robin.<ref name=\"vf\">{{cite web|last=Jessen|first=Philipp|date=April 5, 2007|title=Sarah Connor: Das nackte Leben|work=Vanity Fair Magazine|url=http://www2.vanityfair.de/articles/leute/sarah-connor/2007/04/05/1/00236/|accessdate=2007-06-12 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070515180119/http://www.vanityfair.de/articles/leute/sarah-connor/2007/04/05/1/00236/ |archivedate = May 15, 2007}}</ref> Her maternal half-brothers Mick and Lex were born in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connors Mutter bekommt Zwillinge|website=[[Welt.de]]|url=https://www.welt.de/vermischtes/article2045523/Sarah_Connors_Mutter_bekommt_Zwillinge.html|accessdate=2008-06-19}}</ref> Connor grew up listening to [[soul music]], mostly influenced by her paternal grandfather, a former jazz and R&B [[pianist]] from [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> A church choir provided her with her first experience in [[gospel music]] at the age of six.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> In 1989, the family relocated from [[Hamburg]] to [[Delmenhorst]], where Connor attended the Max-Planck-Gymnasium (high school).<ref name=\"weser2015\">{{cite web|first=Uwe|last=Dammann|title=Doppeltes Heimspiel f\u00fcr Sarah Connor|website=Weser-Kurier.de|url=https://www.weser-kurier.de/bremen/bremen-kultur_artikel,-Doppeltes-Heimspiel-fuer-Sarah-Connor-_arid,1162402.html|date=July 8, 2015|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> She also enrolled at the local performing arts school, where she received dancing, singing, and acting lessons, which she paid for through [[waitressing]] and modelling jobs.<ref name=\"weser2015\"/> After dropping out of school, she completed an internship with [[RTL Television]].<ref name=\"weser2015\"/>\n\nIn 1997, Connor and her sister Anna-Maria were picked to sing with the [[backing singer|backing choir]] during the performances of \"[[Earth Song]]\" and \"[[Heal the World]]\" at [[Michael Jackson]]'s [[HIStory World Tour]] in [[Bremen]], Germany.<ref name=\"vf\"/> Overwhelmed by a personal meeting with Jackson at the end of the show,<ref name=\"vf\"/> she began to record a number of demo tapes under the pseudonym ''Sarah Gray'',<ref name=\"ym\">{{cite web|last=Bonacich|first=Drago|title=Sarah Connors \u2013 Biography|work=Yahoo! Music|url=http://music.yahoo.com/ar-305393-bio--Sarah-Connor|accessdate=2008-06-21}}</ref> including [[cover version]]s such as \"[[Silent Night]]\" and \"[[This Christmas (Donnie Hathaway song)|This Christmas]]\" as well as the local radio success \"Ula la Ula.\"<ref name=\"delorado\">{{cite web|date=August 11, 2005 |title=Sarah Connors Weg zum Erfolg |work=Delorado |url=http://www.deldorado.borgmeier-media.de/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=33&Itemid=33 |accessdate=2008-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517165250/http://www.deldorado.borgmeier-media.de/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=33&Itemid=33 |archivedate=May 17, 2007 }}</ref> In 1998, her boyfriend Martin Scholz, member of the boy band [[Touch\u00e9 (band)|Touch\u00e9]], arranged for Connor to sign a management deal with the group's manager.<ref name=\"delorado\"/> She subsequently served as their opening act for a [[Bremen]] concert in July 1998.<ref name=\"weser2015\"/> Unhappy with her management though, Connor transitioned to the manager Carlo Vista and began work on the single \"This Christmas\" with the producers Oliver Hintz and Thomas N\u00f6hre. It was released through Villa Records in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Gray \u2013 This Christmas|website=[[Discogs]].com|url=https://www.discogs.com/de/Sarah-Gray-This-Christmas/release/7576366|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> Also that year, she provided the leading vocals for the German producer Marc van Linden's [[trance music|trance]] remix of the 1982 record \"[[The Last Unicorn (soundtrack)|Last Unicorn]]\", which reached number eighty-six on the [[German Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marc van Linden - The Last Unicorn|website=AustrianCharts.at|url=https://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Marc+van+Linden&titel=The+Last+Unicorn&cat=s|accessdate=October 6, 2018|language=German}}</ref> In 2000, music manager [[George Glueck]] eventually signed her as ''Sarah Connor'' with the [[Sony]] subsidiary X-Cell Records.<ref name=\"delorado\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===2001\u20132003: Breakthrough with ''From Sarah With Love''===\nConnor fluctuated between Berlin, [[Hamburg]], and [[Hannover]] to work on her [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[hip hop]]-driven debut album, involving German music producers B\u00fclent Aris, Rob Tyger and Kay Denar as well as international collaborators such as [[Kwasi Jones Martin|Eddie Martin]] and rapper [[TQ (singer)|TQ]].<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Its release was preceded by the top five and top 20 hit singles \"[[Let's Get Back to Bed \u2013 Boy!]]\" and \"[[French Kissing]]\", respectively, as well as her breakthrough hit, the ballad \"[[From Sarah with Love]]\", which reached the top position in Germany, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland and raised Connor's fame all over Europe.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Eventually released in November 2001, ''[[Green Eyed Soul (Sarah Connor album)|Green Eyed Soul]]'' generally mixed reception from music critics, who declared it a mixed bag but considered it a solid career launcher.<ref name=\"laut.de\">{{cite web |last=Fr\u00f6mmer |first=Michael |url=http://www.laut.de/lautstark/cd-reviews/c/connor_sarah/green_eyed_soul/index.htm |title=G\u00e4ngige R'n'B Grooves, zeitgem\u00e4\u00dfe Hip Hop-Muster, Pop Beats \u00e0 la Britney|language=German |publisher=laut.de |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> The album debuted at number two on the [[Media Control Charts|German Albums Chart]], and charted within the top five in Austria, Finland and Switzerland, reaching gold status in Austria, Czech, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland, while earning platinum certifications in Finland and Germany.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Connor was subsequently awarded a [[Goldene Europa]] and won the [[Echo Music Prize|Echo Music Prize for Best National Rock/Pop Female Artist]], among three nominations.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/>\n\n[[File:Sarah Connor 4.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Connor in 2002 at ''[[Verstehen Sie Spa\u00df?]]'']] The following year, Connor embarked on the Green Eyed Soul Tour in 2002 and began production on her second studio album ''[[Unbelievable (Sarah Connor album)|Unbelievable]]''. A continuation of ''Green Eyed Soul'', she reteamed with Aris, Denar and Tyger to work on the majority of the album, with American musicians [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Jerry Duplessis]], and [[Diane Warren]] also joining the project.<ref name=\"focus2002\"/> Jean wrote, produced and rapped on the album's [[lead single]], \"[[One Nite Stand (of Wolves and Sheep)]]\", which once again entered the top 5. ''Unbelievable'' simultaneously achieved gold status in Germany within 48 hours and spawned another three singles, including \"[[Skin on Skin (Sarah Connor song)|Skin on Skin]]\", \"[[He's Unbelievable]]\" and \"[[Bounce (Sarah Connor Song)|Bounce]]\".\n\nIn October 2003, Connor released a live DVD branded ''Sarah Connor Live \u2013 [[A Night to Remember: Pop Meets Classic]]'', whose performance had been recorded at the Alten Kasselhaus in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] on January 24, including individual performances of own songs with a classical orchestra backing her up. In November 2003, in spite of being heavily pregnant with her first child, Connor released her third album called, ''[[Key to My Soul]]''. The album's first single, \"[[Music Is the Key]]\" featuring New York [[a cappella]] singers [[Naturally 7]], became her second number-one hit in Germany. \"[[Just One Last Dance]]\", the album's second and final single, was a re-recorded edition of the album's original version, including new vocals by Marc Terenzi's band [[Natural (band)|Natural]]. The duet once again reached number-one in Austria, Germany, and Switzerland and the top 20 on a composite World Top 40.\n\nThe album ''[[Sarah Connor (album)|Sarah Connor]]'' featured the first single, \"Bounce\". It was released in many countries, including Japan, Australia, New Zealand, Canada and the United States. In Germany, the single made it to #14 on the charts. In England and Ireland it peaked at number 14 and was certified gold in Australia.  In America, the song only managed a #54 on the Billboard Hot 100.  The album made it to number 106 and took off in the U.S., selling almost 100.000 copies.\n\n===2004\u20132008: International success===\nAfter a lengthy hiatus that saw the birth of her son Tyler, Connor returned to music in fall 2004 with the release of her single \"[[Living to Love You]].\" The ballad reached number-one in Germany and Switzerland, becoming her third consecutive chart-topper, and preceded her fourth album ''[[Naughty But Nice (album)|Naughty But Nice]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 Living To Love You|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/3226|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Connor re-teamed with longtime contributors Booya, Kay Denar und Rob Tyger to work on the album, whose release coincided with the \nbroadcast of her [[ProSieben]] reality series ''[[Sarah & Marc in Love]]''. Her highest-charting effort yet, ''Naughty But Nice'' debuted on top of the German Albums Chart and reached the top three in Austria and Switzerland, selling 100,000 copies within the first two days of its release.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 ''Naughty But Nice'' |publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/album/18027|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Critical reaction towards the album was generally mixed, with [[Allmusic]] rating it three starts out of five,<ref>{{cite web|title=''Naughty but Nice'' review|website=[[Allmusic]]|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r740510|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> and ''laut.de'' summing it as \"underclass music for the disco around the corner.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Schuh|title=Unterschichtenmusik F\u00fcr Die Dorfdisco Um Die Ecke|publisher=laut.de|url=http://www.laut.de/Sarah-Connor/Naughty-But-Nice-(Album)|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Spawning just one another single, \"[[From Zero to Hero]]\" was picked to be used as the theme song to the [[computer-animated]] movie ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' (2005),The song became her fifth chart-topping single in Germany and the fourth number-one hit single in a row.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 From Zero To Hero|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/3300|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SarahConnorEinZuhausef\u00fcrKinder.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Connor performing live in 2008]]\nIn fall 2005, Connor embarked on the [[Naughty But Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice concert tour]]. Compiling twenty-three dates in Austria, Germany and Switzerland, the tour concluded a month later. In December 2005, she released a [[holiday album]] named ''[[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor album)|Christmas in My Heart]]''. Containing a mix of traditional but contemporary English standards and re-written German songs in English language, both the album and its [[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor song)|same-titled lead single]] reached number four on the charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 ''Christmas in My Heart''|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/album/18170|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'Christmas in My Heart'|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/7345|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Eventually certified platinum by the [[IFPI]],<ref name=\"cert\">{{cite certification|region=Germany|artist=Sarah Connor|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> the album was re-released the following year, including the previously unreleased single \"[[The Best Side of Life]],\" another top four success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'The Best Side of Life'|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/11581|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref>\n\nReturning from yet another hiatus after the birth of her daughter Summer in 2006, Connor released her sixth studio album ''[[Soulicious (Sarah Connor album)|Soulicious]]'' in March 2007. Mainly made up of 1960s and 70s [[Motown]] covers, but also including two original songs, recording for the entire album took place at the former main building of the [[Berliner Rundfunk]], where Connor was backed by a symphonic orchestra of forty-eight musicians.<ref>{{cite web|title=Information on ''Soulicious''|publisher=SarahConnor.com|url=http://www.sarah-connor.com/de/media/discography/album/soulicious.html|accessdate=2010-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107185321/http://www.sarah-connor.com/de/media/discography/album/soulicious.html|archivedate=2011-01-07}}</ref> Upon its release, the album reached the top ten in Austria, Germany and Switzerland, where it each reached gold status.<ref name=\"cert\"/> Critics, again, gave ''Soulicious'' a mixed response, with ''CDStarts.de'' calling it \"a sterile soul adaption for ''[[The Dome (television program)|The Dome]]'' stage.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Matthias|last=Reichel|title=''Soulicious'' Review|publisher=CDStarts.de|url=http://www.cdstarts.de/kritiken/88956-Soulicious.html|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> Leading single \"[[The Impossible Dream (The Quest)]],\" which was featured in a publicity campaign for the comeback fight of German [[Boxing|boxer]] [[Henry Maske]], and \"[[Sexual Healing#Sarah Connor version|Sexual Healing]],\" a duet with American singer [[Ne-Yo]], reached the top ten and top twenty of the singles charts respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'The Impossible Dream '|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/12488|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor and Ne-Yo \u2013 'Sexual Healing'|publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/26859|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref>\n\nHeading into a new musical direction, Connor intensified work on her next original album with producers such as [[Remee]], [[Thomas Troelsen]] and [[J. R. Rotem]]. In May 2008, it was announced Connor and her family would once again participate in an eight-part reality show titled ''Sarah and Marc: Still Crazy in Love\"'' on [[ProSieben]]. The special began airing on July 3, 2008, and followed the recording and promotional events for the new album, branded ''[[Sexy as Hell]]''.<ref>[http://www.prosieben.de/music_cd/samil/artikel/52525/ TV: Serien & Sendungen von ProSieben]. Prosieben.de. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080601073820/http://unterhaltung.de.msn.com/stars/news-artikel.aspx?cp-documentid=8346012 Sarah und Marc mit neuer Liebesdoku]. MSN.com (in German). May 21, 2008</ref> Its first single, \"[[Under My Skin (Sarah Connor song)|Under My Skin]],\" co-written by Troelsen, was released on August 1, 2008, in [[German-speaking Europe]], with the album following on August 22, 2008. Subsequently, she was nominated for an ECHO.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n===2009\u2013present: ''X-Factor'', ''Real Love'' and ''Muttersprache''===\n[[File:Sarah Connor Bremen1.jpg|thumbnail|Sarah Connor performing at the Muttersprache Tour in March 2016]]\nIn 2009, Connor contributed to a re-recorded version of [[Enrique Iglesias]]' duet \"[[Takin' Back My Love]],\" replacing American singer [[Ciara]]'s original vocals on the song. Released as the second single from Iglesias' 2008 ''[[Greatest Hits (Enrique Iglesias album)|Greatest Hits]]'' album in [[German-speaking Europe]], Poland and the [[Czech Republic]], it reached the top ten of the German Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enrique Iglesias and Sarah Connor \u2013 Takin Back My Love |publisher=aCharts.us|url=http://acharts.us/song/43299|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> In April 2010, it was announced that Connor would appear alongside mentor George Glueck and musician [[Till Br\u00f6nner]] as a judge on the debut series of ''[[X Factor (Germany)|X Factor]]'', broadcast on the German [[VOX (German TV channel)|VOX]] network.<ref name=\"gala\">[http://www.gala.de/stars/news/96648/Sarah-Connor-Jurorin-bei-X-Factor.html Sarah Connor: Jurorin bei \"X Factor\" \u2013 News auf]. Gala.de. March 8, 2010. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> Connor was given the 16-24s category (made up of solo contestants between 16 and 24) but failed to reach the final show when her contestant [[Mati Gavriel]] was eliminated in his seventh week and [[Edita Abdieski]] was crowned the winner of ''X Factor'' instead.<ref name=\"gala\"/> Amid her appearances on ''X Factor'', Connor released her eighth studio album ''[[Real Love (Sarah Connor album)|Real Love]]'' on October 22, 2010. It earned a lukewarm reception by critics,<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah-Nina|last=Rademacher|url=http://www.laut.de/Sarah-Connor/Real-Love-(Album)|title=Sarah, du hast den X-Factor ...|accessdate=2010-11-06|work=laut.de}}</ref> and debuted at number eight on the [[German Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"acharts\">{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/album/58333|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 ''Real Love'' Music Charts |accessdate=2010-11-06|work=\u03b1Charts.us}}</ref> Altogether, ''Real Love'' produced two singles, including \"[[Cold as Ice (Sarah Connor song)|Cold as Ice]],\" which reached the top twenty on the [[German Singles Chart]], and its [[Real Love (Sarah Connor song)|title track]], both of which became her lowest-charting singles in years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/song/58072|title=Sarah Connor \u2013 'Cold As Ice' Music Charts |accessdate=2010-11-06|work=\u03b1Charts.us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beatblogger.de/vo-vorschau/|title=V\u00d6-Vorschau|accessdate=2010-11-06|work=Beatblogger.de}}</ref> Connor returned for the second and third ''X Factor'' series in 2011 and 2012 and was given the groups and over 25s categories, respecitvely. Again, her contestants Nica & Joe and Bj\u00f6rn Paulsen each placed third, losing to [[David Pfeffer]] and [[Mrs. Greenbird]].<ref name=\"gala\"/>\n\nFollowing a hiatus, in 2014, Connor appeared in the reality television series ''[[Sing meinen Song - Das Tauschkonzert]]'', the German version of ''[[The Best Singers (series)|The Best Singers]]'' series. In 2015, Connor released her ninth studio album ''[[Muttersprache (album)|Muttersprache]]'', her first album to be entirely recorded in [[German language|German]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite web|date=2006-02-01|title=Muttersprache (Deluxe Version)|publisher=Play.Google.de|url=https://play.google.com/store/music/album/Sarah_Connor_Muttersprache_Deluxe_Version?id=Byjmelola4mbdegqtkjif6zbom4&PAffiliateID=11lxBw|accessdate=2015-04-20}}</ref> Encouraged to record songs in her native language, following her performances on ''Sing meinen Song'', Connor worked with a smaller range of producers on the album, including Daniel Faust, [[Peter Plate]], and Ulf Leo Sommer. Upon its release, ''Muttersprache'' debuted on top of on the [[GfK Entertainment|German Albums Chart]], becoming her second number-one album following 2005's ''[[Naughty but Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice]]''. With first week sales of more than 100,000 copies in Germany, ''Muttersprache'' was certified [[List of music recording certifications|gold]] by the [[Bundesverband Musikindustrie]] (BVMI) just days after its release.<ref name=\"pp\">{{cite web|date=2006-06-03|title=SARAH CONNOR: Platz #1 in den Offiziellen Deutschen Albumcharts|publisher=Presseportal|url=http://www.presseportal.de/pm/58621/3038018|accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref> It has since been certified [[List of music recording certifications|platinum]].<ref name=\"uv\">{{cite web|title=Universal-Vertriebstagung 2015 \u2013 Briegmann: \"Wachstum ohne Streaming ist nicht denkbar\"|publisher=Musikmarkt.de|url=http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|accessdate=2015-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019032132/http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|archive-date=October 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album also debuted at number-one on the [[Swiss Albums Chart]], her first album to do so.<ref name=\"pp\"/> \"[[Wie sch\u00f6n du bist]]\" became Connor's highest-charting single in a decade, reaching number two on the [[German Singles Chart]], and sold over 260,000 copies.<ref name=\"uv\">{{cite web|title=Universal-Vertriebstagung 2015 \u2013 Briegmann: \"Wachstum ohne Streaming ist nicht denkbar\"|publisher=Musikmarkt.de|url=http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|accessdate=2015-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019032132/http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Vertriebstagung-2015-Briegmann-Wachstum-ohne-Streaming-ist-nicht-denkbar|archive-date=October 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nConnor met [[Marc Terenzi]], the lead singer of American boy band [[Natural (band)|Natural]], at the Bravo Happy Holidays festival in [[Rust, Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|Rust]], Germany in July 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor Und Marc Terenzi Gmeinsam Im Exklusiven Interview|url=http://www.presseportal.de/pm/13440/373742/bravo|date=August 20, 2002|work=BRAVO|publisher=Presseportal.de|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> The pair began dating and in June 2003, it was announced they were engaged and expecting their first child, Tyler Marc Terenzi, who was born on February 2, 2004 in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Popstar-Liebe: Sarah Connor Ist Mutter|url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/0,1518,284737,00.html|magazine=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=March 2, 2004|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> On February 29, 2004 the couple invited their friends to a dinner supposedly to celebrate the birth of their son; however they announced that they in fact had eloped. The couple renewed their vows this time with a wedding ceremony on August 18, 2005 in Altafulla, [[Tarragon\u00e8s]], near [[Barcelona, Spain]]. The wedding was the subject of their ProSieben reality show ''[[Sarah and Marc in Love]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor (24) \u2013 Ein Pop-Produkt Wird Besichtigt|url=http://www.dk-online.de/Nachrichten/Archiv/index.csp?artikel=784027|publisher=DK-Online.de|date=May 5, 2005|accessdate=2010-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718231933/http://www.dk-online.de/Nachrichten/Archiv/index.csp?artikel=784027|archivedate=July 18, 2011}}</ref> On June 23, 2006, Connor gave birth to their second child, a girl, named Summer Antonia Soraya.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Herzfehler \u2013 Sarah Connor Bangt Um Tochter|url=http://www.stern.de/lifestyle/leute/herzfehler-sarah-connor-bangt-um-tochter-564391.html|magazine=[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]]|date=June 19, 2006|accessdate=2010-10-29}}</ref> In November 2008, Connor announced her separation from Terenzi.\n\nIn April 2010, Connor announced that she is in a relationship with her manager, Florian Fischer, the singer of the 1990s pop group The Boyz.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Connor Ist Nach Scheidung Wieder Liiert|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/vermischtes/article1673152/Sarah-Connor-ist-nach-Scheidung-wieder-liiert.html|date=October 24, 2010|work=[[Hamburger Abendblatt]]|publisher=Abendblatt.de|accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref> In February 2011, the two confirmed that they were expecting a child.<ref>{{in lang|de}} [http://www.bild.de/BILD/unterhaltung/leute/2011/02/21/sarah-connor/im-vierten-monat-schwanger-baby-mit-florian-fischer.html Pop-S\u00e4ngerin freut sich auf ihr 3. Baby: Sarah Connor im 4. Monat schwanger \u2013 Leute]. Bild.de. February 21, 2011. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> Their daughter Delphine Malou was born in September 2011. They welcomed their son Jax Llewyn in January 2017.<ref>http://www.zeit.de/news/2017-01/18/leute-sarah-connor-bringt-soehnchen-jax-llewyn-zur-welt-18072008</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sarah Connor discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Green Eyed Soul]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Unbelievable (Sarah Connor album)|Unbelievable]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Key to My Soul]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Naughty but Nice (album)|Naughty but Nice]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Christmas in My Heart (Sarah Connor album)|Christmas in My Heart]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Soulicious (Sarah Connor album)|Soulicious]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Sexy as Hell]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Real Love (Sarah Connor album)|Real Love]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Muttersprache (album)|Muttersprache]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Herz Kraft Werke]]'' (2019)\n\n==Tours==\n* Green Eyed Soul Tour (2002)\n* Sarah Connor Live (2003\u20132004)\n* Naughty but Nice Tour (2005)\n* Sexy as Hell Tour (2009)\n* Sarah Connor China Tour (Beijing/Guangzhou) (2010\u20132012)\n* Christmas in My Heart Live (2012\u20132013)\n* Muttersprache Live (2015\u20132017)\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=4 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Television guest appearances\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Role\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| \"[[Sarah & Marc in Love]]\"\n| Herself\n| Reality Television\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"[[Sarah & Marc Crazy in Love]]\"\n| Herself\n| Reality Television, Promo for ''[[Sexy as Hell]]''\n|-\n|2009\n|Leo Piepmatz rockt das Haus: Eine Mut-Mach-Geschichte f\u00fcr kleine L\u00f6wen und gro\u00dfe Rockstars\n| Herself\n| Audiobook \n|-\n| 2010\u20132012\n| \"[[The X Factor (UK)|X-Factor]]\"\n| Herself\n| Main juror\n|-\n|2014\n| [[Sing meinen Song - Das Tauschkonzert]]\n| Herself\n| Television Music Show by VOX <br> Season 1\n|-\n|2014\n| [[Sing meinen Song